{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502464"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:44:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:44:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1863"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1863"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.7,0.07,0.02,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1863"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106593"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1863"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1863"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89067"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"4159"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39382"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106593"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of colicky abdominal pain, distension and vomiting. She has a medical history of hypertension and myocardial infarction with stent insertion two years ago. She had an appendicectomy at the age of 22. Her medications include clopidogrel, aspirin and perindopril. She has no relevant social or travel history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with pulse rate 100/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She has a soft, distended abdomen with high-pitched bowel sounds. There is an easily reducible and non-tender right inguinal hernia. Plain abdominal radiograph shows dilated small bowel loops with air-fluid levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Incarcerated inguinal hernia","Adhesions","Carcinoma of the caecum","Retroperitoneal haemorrhage","Intussusception of small bowel"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of small bowel obstruction: colicky abdominal pain, distension, vomiting, and high-pitched bowel sounds. The most common cause of small bowel obstruction is \u003Cstrong\u003Eadhesions\u003C/strong\u003E, which typically develop following previous abdominal surgery. Despite the appendicectomy being performed over 50 years ago, adhesions can cause obstruction at any time after surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eincarcerated inguinal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when bowel becomes trapped within the hernia sac and cannot be reduced. However, this patient\u0027s hernia is easily reducible, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the caecum\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes large bowel obstruction rather than small bowel obstruction. While it can occasionally present with small bowel obstruction due to backpressure or ileocaecal valve incompetence, adhesions remain a far more likely cause given the surgical history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetroperitoneal haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare complication of anticoagulation therapy that can cause paralytic ileus. However, this would present with absent or diminished bowel sounds rather than the high-pitched sounds characteristic of mechanical obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntussusception of small bowel\u003C/strong\u003E is rare in adults and typically occurs in the presence of a pathological lead point such as a tumour, polyp, or Meckel\u0027s diverticulum. In this elderly patient with a history of previous surgery and no other concerning features, adhesions remain the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of previous abdominal surgery, mechanical obstruction features, and the absence of other specific findings strongly supports adhesions as the most likely cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adhesions from previous abdominal surgery are the most common cause of small bowel obstruction, regardless of time elapsed since surgery.","High-pitched bowel sounds with colicky pain, distension and vomiting are classic features of mechanical small bowel obstruction.","Intussusception in adults is rare and usually associated with a pathological lead point such as a tumour."],"references":["Podda M, Khan M, Di Saverio S. Adhesive small bowel obstruction and the six w\u2019s: Who, how, why, when, what, and where to diagnose and operate? Scand J Surg 2021; 110:159\u201369. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33511902/","Schick MA, Kashyap S, Collier SA, et al. Small Bowel Obstruction. [Updated 2025 Jan 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448079/","Aka AA, Wright JP, DeBeche-Adams T. Small Bowel Obstruction. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2021 Jul;34(4):219-226. doi: 10.1055/s-0041-1725204. Epub 2021 Jul 20. PMID: 34305470; PMCID: PMC8292006. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8292006/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89067"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1863"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89067"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-20T20:29:49+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-20T20:29:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1863"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106593"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedA